<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="227" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1633,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1633,1658]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Large species with body length 
<number box="[687,735,1634,1658]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="10.5">10.5</number>
–15.0 mm. Head strongly rounded behind eyes in dorsal view. Upper tooth of mandible longer than lower tooth. Clypeus large, lenticular, coarsely and densely punctate except lower margin. Malar space 
<number box="[470,555,1706,1730]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="0.55" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.6</number>
× as long as basal width of mandible. Flagellum of antenna unusually short, narrowed towards apex, with 
<number box="[482,551,1742,1766]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="31.5" valueMax="36.0" valueMin="27.0">27–36</number>
flagellomeres (
<figureCitation box="[726,810,1742,1766]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">
Fig. 
<number box="[778,810,1742,1766]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="20.0">20</number>
</figureCitation>
); all flagellomeres, except the basal and the apical ones, distinctly transverse. Occipital carina complete. Hypostomal carina absent. Mesoscutum flattened, low in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[221,307,1814,1838]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">
Fig. 
<number box="[275,307,1814,1838]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
). Notaulus weak. Prepectal carina not joining to anterior margin of mesopleuron, dorsally indistinct (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,1850,1874]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">
Fig. 
<number box="[211,243,1850,1874]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
). Subtegular ridge strongly raised in frontal view, projecting laterally. Foveate groove of mesopleuron deep and long, coarsely crenulate, weakly curved, extending from anterior margin of mesopleuron to base of mid coxa (
<figureCitation box="[159,246,1922,1946]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,246,1922,1946]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
). Propodeum and metapleuron coarsely and irregularly rugose (
<figureCitation box="[979,1066,1922,1946]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">
Fig. 
<number box="[1035,1066,1922,1946]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="23.0">23</number>
</figureCitation>
). Distance between spiracle and pleural carina about half diameter of spiracle. Fore wing with vein 
<number box="[920,934,1958,1982]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[934,990,1959,1982]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">m-cu</emphasis>
postfurcal. Veins 
<emphasis box="[1198,1226,1959,1982]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">Rs</emphasis>
+ 
<number box="[1241,1255,1958,1982]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[1255,1266,1959,1982]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">r</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1324,1352,1959,1982]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">Rs</emphasis>
angled about 
<number box="[220,266,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="125.0">125</number>
°. Vein 
<number box="[347,361,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[361,412,1995,2018]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">rs-m</emphasis>
twice longer than abscissa of 
<emphasis box="[752,775,1995,2018]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">M</emphasis>
between 
<number box="[883,897,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[897,948,1995,2018]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">rs-m</emphasis>
and 
<number box="[1004,1018,1994,2018]" pageId="5" pageNumber="226" value="2.0">2</number>
<emphasis box="[1018,1074,1995,2018]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="226">m-cu</emphasis>
, both these veins not thickened.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">
<collectingCountry box="[151,207,151,175]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">Hind</collectingCountry>
wing with vein 
<emphasis box="[401,427,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">cu</emphasis>
<number box="[428,438,151,175]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" value="1.0">1</number>
&amp; 
<emphasis box="[463,513,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">cu-a</emphasis>
subvertical. 
<collectingCountry box="[663,719,151,175]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">Hind</collectingCountry>
femur distinctly clavate (
<figureCitation box="[1019,1105,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">
Fig. 
<number box="[1074,1105,151,175]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
). Spurs of hind tibia weakly curved at apex. Tarsal claws not pectinate. Metasomal segment 
<number box="[871,885,188,212]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" value="1.0">1</number>
slender, without glymma, round in cross-section (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1245,1268]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1224]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 23. Megalochus grandis sp. nov., Ƥ: 20 — head with antennae, frontal; 21 — hind leg and base of metasoma, left; 22 — mesosoma, left; 23 — propodeum, posterolateral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249397/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,243,223,247]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
). Thyridial depression very long. Ovipositor upcurved, without teeth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="227" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,260,284]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the 
<collectingCountry box="[454,533,260,284]" name="Greece" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">Greece</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[541,601,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">mega</emphasis>
(large) and the latter part of the generic name 
<taxonomicName box="[1137,1265,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Tersilochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1137,1265,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">Tersilochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, on account of the large body size. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,356]" box="[199,1101,331,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,359,331,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">Composition.</emphasis>
Only one species is known, 
<taxonomicName box="[679,802,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Megalochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[679,802,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">M. grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[809,899,332,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[809,899,332,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="227">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, described below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
